Extend /boot Using New Disk (/dev/sdb) - Complete
Procedure
1. Verify disks
lsblk
fdisk -l
2. Create partition on new disk
fdisk /dev/sdb
Inside fdisk:
n
p
1
<Enter>
<Enter>
w
3. Create filesystem
mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1
4. Create mount point
mkdir /mnt/newboot
5. Mount new partition
mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/newboot
6. Copy boot contents
cp -ax /boot/* /mnt/newboot/
7. Get UUID
blkid /dev/sdb1
8. Backup fstab
cp -p /etc/fstab /etc/fstab.bkp
9. Modify /etc/fstab
Replace old /boot UUID with UUID of /dev/sdb1
10. Unmount temporary mount
umount /mnt/newboot
11. Mount using fstab
mount -a
Verify:
df -h /boot
mount | grep boot
12. BIOS systems
grub2-install /dev/sda
grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
13. Reboot
reboot
14. Verify
df -h /boot
lsblk
Note:
Current /boot has approximately 660 MB free, which is generally sufficient for RHEL 8.10 to RHEL 9.7 
